## Configuring a record
This feature allows to view and edit the configuration details of the selected record.

- Click on the name of a record to view its details; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Configure the required fields:

**Parameter**

**Description**

**Name**

Name of the new record

**Character separator**

*(only available for character-separated files)*

Character used in the Flat file to separate records; the possible options are: 

Colon (:)

- Comma (,) 

- Pipe (|) 

- Pound (#)

- Semicolon (;)

- Space

- Tab

**Identifiers**

View and configure record identifiers and recognition rules. For more information, see [Managing record identifiers and recognition rules](#_bookmark46) below.

**Fields**

View and configure all the fields of the record.

### Managing record identifiers and recognition rules
In the **Identifiers **section, you can view and configure one or more record identifiers and combine them using logical operators; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

The system assigns an alphanumeric code to the identifiers, consisting of two letters indicating the identifier's type followed by an incremental number.

The two letters indicate the type of identifier:

- **SD**: Fixed identifier

- **FD**: Positional identifier

The number indicates the position of the identifier within the record (for example: **SD2**).

#### Adding an identifier to a character-separated record
- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add identifier**) on the top-right. The following configuration window is displayed:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- In the **Start position **field, enter the record column from which to start extracting the text to compare.

> Note

The number of characters to be extracted is equal to the length of the text entered in the value field.

- In the **Value **field, enter the comparison value.

- Select the **Add another **option to save changes and add another identifier after this one.

- Click **Add field **to confirm and create the new identifier.

#### Adding an identifier to a fixed structure record
- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add identifier**) on the top-right. The following configuration window is displayed:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Select the type of identifier to create; the possible options are:

**Positional identifier**: Identify a value in a given position of the record by specifying a number of separator characters and a comparison value.

- **Fixed identifier**: Identify a value in a given position of the record by specifying a start position and a comparison value.

- Depending on your selection, fill in the required parameters:

**Type**

**Configuration**

**Positional identifier**

In the **Separator count **field, enter the number of separator characters that are found before the identifier value.

- In the **Value **field, enter the comparison value.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

**Fixed identifier**

- In the **Start position **field, enter t he record column from which to start extracting the text to compare.

> Note

The number of characters to be extracted is equal to the length of the text entered in the value field.

- In the **Value **field, enter the comparison value.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Select the **Add another **option to save changes and add another identifier after this one.

- Click **Add field **to confirm and create the new identifier.

#### Defining the recognition rule using a logical expression
This feature allows to correlate two or more record identifiers by defining a logical expression using Boolean operators.

The functionality is useful, for example, when one identifier is not enough to recognize a record in the Flat File and a complex logical expression is required.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Identifiers **section, add the required identifiers, as described in:

[Adding an identifier to a character-separated record](#_bookmark49)

- [Adding an identifier to a fixed structure record](#_bookmark51)

> Note

By default, the system automatically adds new identifiers to the logical expression area and combines them using the boolean operator AND.

- If required, edit the identifiers as described in [Editing an identifier](#_bookmark53) above.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the logical expression area, concatenate identifiers using boolean operators; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Drag &amp; drop an identifier from the table into the logical expression area to add it to the condition.

- Click on a Boolean operator icon to add it to the expression; the available operators are:

 **AND**

- **OR**

- **NOT**

- **(**

- **)**

> Tip

You can drag &amp; drop identifiers and Boolean operators within the logical expression to rearrange them.

To delete an identifier or a boolean operator from the logical expression area, move your mouse pointer over the corresponding placeholder and click ![](data:image/png;base64,) .

> Tip

Click the **CHECK **link on the bottom-right of the logical expression area to check the correctness of the logical expression. The system will perform a syntax check and displays a status message with the result; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Managing fields
In the **Fields **section, you can view and configure all the fields of the record (parsable by position or fixed length).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Adding a field
- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add field**) on the top-right. The following configuration window is displayed:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Enter the **Name **of the field identifier.

- In the **Position **field, enter the relative position of the field in a character delimited format (the starting position is **0**).

- Enter the **Default value **of the field, to be used when the read value is null or blank.

- Select the **Optional **checkbox to indicate that the field is optional.

> Note

If not selected, it means that null values are not accepted.

- Expand the **Advanced settings **section to configure the padding and trim parameters:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

**Field**

**Description**

**Padding**

Configure the **Padding **option to replace the leading and trailing blank spaces with the specified character:

**None**: Apply no padding (default value).

- **Left**: Apply padding to the left side of the string.

- **Right**: Apply padding to the right side of the string.

**Trim**

Configure the **Trim **option to delete all unnecessary blank spaces from the selected sides of the string:

- **None**: Apply no trim, leave the string as is.

- **Both**: Delete blank spaces on both sides (left and right).

- **Left**: Delete blank spaces from the leftmost character up to the first non-blank leftmost character.

- **Right**: Delete blank spaces from the rightmost character up to the first non-blank rightmost character.

**Padding character**

Enter the character to use for the padding (if enabled).

**Padding length**

Enter the total length that the string needs to reach using padding (if enabled). The specified character will be added in the selected direction until the configured length is reached.

- Select the **Add another **option to save changes and add another identifier after this one.

- Click **Add field **to confirm.
